</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE936E4E270BF5AFF586E977C9FFC5A" blockId="11.[151,1436,746,972]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName id="4C564D67E270BF5AFF586E977957FC95" box="[151,293,746,771]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Houardiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B922EAF6E270BF5AFF586E977957FC95" box="[151,293,746,771]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Houardiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises two described species in the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D67E270BF5AFCF36E977B96FC92" box="[828,996,746,772]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Asphondyliini">Asphondyliini</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC74B15E270BF5AFC3B6E977CF8FC92" author="Gagne" box="[1012,1162,746,772]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refString="Gagne, R. J. (2004) A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Washington 25, 1 - 408." type="journal article" year="2004">
Gagné 
<number id="3D9E24C3E270BF5AFB856E977CF8FC92" box="[1098,1162,746,772]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It is closely related to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D67E270BF5AFEC26F6F79D2FCBD" box="[269,416,786,811]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B922EAF6E270BF5AFEC26F6F79D2FCBD" box="[269,416,786,811]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Asphondylia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with its needle-like, piercing ovipositor that is accompanied by a pair of basal lobes at its base, and the progressively shorter flagellomeres in the female. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D67E270BF5AFB976F477C99FCC5" box="[1112,1259,826,851]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B922EAF6E270BF5AFB976F477C99FCC5" box="[1112,1259,826,851]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Asphondylia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having onesegmented (as opposed to three-segmented) palpi, a single tooth rather than two teeth on the male gonostylus, and an apical, posterior extension of the gonocoxite. Immature stages resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C564D67E270BF5AFB0B6FF77D25FC35" box="[1220,1367,906,931]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Asphondylia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B922EAF6E270BF5AFB0B6FF77D25FC35" box="[1220,1367,906,931]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Asphondylia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with well developed cephalic horns and abdominal spines in pupae, and a massive spatula in larvae.
</paragraph>
